This is the **SKILL.md** file — the gold standard specification for the `mini-theory-of-computation` project. Here's a summary of its structure:

---

### Core Philosophy
- **Dual Standard**: Every sub-module must have both **≥3,000 lines** of code (in `include/` + `src/`, excluding `.lean`, tests, examples) AND full knowledge coverage across 9 levels.
- **Code is the carrier of knowledge** — one knowledge point → one natural implementation → one test → one example.

---

### Nine-Layer Knowledge System (L1–L9)

| Level | Name | Example Topics |
|-------|------|----------------|
| L1 | Definitions | P, NP, Turing machine, circuit family |
| L2 | Core Concepts | Polynomial time, non-determinism, diagonalization |
| L3 | Mathematical Structures | Turing machine formal tuple, Boolean circuits, DNF/CNF |
| L4 | Fundamental Laws | Cook-Levin Theorem, Time Hierarchy, Savitch's Theorem |
| L5 | Algorithms/Methods | DPLL/CDCL SAT, switching lemma, IP=PSPACE |
| L6 | Canonical Problems | SAT, 3SAT, CLIQUE, HAM-PATH, TQBF |
| L7 | Applications | Cryptography, formal verification, PAC learning |
| L8 | Advanced Topics | PCP Theorem, circuit lower bounds, natural proofs |
| L9 | Research Frontiers | Meta-complexity, GCT, quantum complexity |

---

### Key Rules and Prohibitions

- **Anti-Filler Iron Law**: No loop-generated stubs, no same-pattern function bodies repeated >3 times, no dead code files just to pad line counts.
- **Lean 4 rules**: No `by trivial` on non-trivial propositions, no `sorry`, no cross-file copy-paste of same code blocks, no `axiom` for provable theorems.
- **Completion requires**: L1–L6 **Complete**, L7–L8 **Partial+**, L9 **Partial**.

---

### Audit & Safety Review
- Deep audit scripts checking each of the 9 layers
- **Filler detection scans** (grep for patterns like `_fn[0-9]`, `_aux[0-9]`, `by trivial`, `sorry`)
- **Zero tolerance** for detected fillers — must be removed or replaced

---

### Project Structure
The project is organized into sub-modules like `mini-cook-levin-theorem/`, `mini-switching-lemma/`, `mini-boolean-circuits-model/`, etc., under themes such as circuit complexity, algorithmic complexity, and complexity foundations.

This is essentially a rigorous, self-enforcing specification for building a comprehensive, code-backed theory of computation knowledge base.
